full functionality of researchgate it is necessary to enable javascript here are the instructions how to enable javascript in your web browser see all › citationssee all › referencesshare facebook twitter google linkedin reddit download fulltext pdf the impact of marketing on customer equity from relationship marketing to product marketingarticle with  readsst shijin yoond dominique hanssens · university of california los angelesdiscover the worlds research million members million publicationsk research projectsjoin for free the impact of marketing on customer equity from relationship marketing to product marketing shijin yoo and dominique m hanssens♦ january  ♦ shijin yoo is a doctoral candidate and dominique m hanssens is the bud knapp professor of marketing at the ucla anderson school of management abstract the customer equity ce concept has been successfully applied to relationship businesses such as banking insurance and telecommunications this paper takes the ce framework to productmarketing industries eg consumer durables by developing a model that can infer the impact of marketing mix efforts on ce each brand’s acquisition rates and retention rates two core elements of ce are measured by decomposing the source of product sales into two parts existing customers and prospects a vectorautoregressive var model is proposed to estimate the dynamic relationship between the marketing mix and ce the model is applied to the automobile industry as an empirical illustration by comparing the ce model to the conventional sales response model we find that the impact of the marketing mix on ce is different from its impact on sales while both discounting and advertising increase product sales this saleseffectiveness is not directly translated to the development of ce in the longrun brands differ in the impact of discounting on acquisition vs retention rates higher quality brands are more acquisitioneffective while lower quality brands are more retentioneffective only one brand increases its longterm acquisition rate by advertising and none of the brands increase longrun retention through advertising advertising’s shortterm impact on acquisition rate differs across brands while advertisements by smallshare and cheaper brands have a negative impact on acquisition rate largeshare and more expensive brands increase their acquisition rates by advertising efforts the managerial implications of the model are shown by simulating the changes induced by an incremental marketing investment in the number of customers profits and ultimately customer equity over time introduction customer equity ce has emerged as a new paradigm for guiding managers to build strong and profitable relationships between the customer and the firm the framework regards customers as a valuable asset that should be managed like any other financial assets blattberg and deighton  given its emphasis on a customercentered marketing strategy it is not surprising that the ce paradigm has been applied primarily to the relationshipmarketing domain examples include insurance jackson  newspapers keane and wang  magazines dwyer  cellular phones bolton  airline pilot memberships thomas  and interactive television entertainment services lemon white and winer  however in most industries managers make their marketing decisions based on productbased metrics such as sales and market share as noted by rust lemon and zeithaml  “business success is based on customer relationships however because customer equity is difficult to measure many companies continue to focus on metrics that capture productbased strategies rather than metrics that capture customerbased strategies” for example managers dealing with frequently purchased consumer goods fpcg or consumer durables have difficulty applying the ce paradigm to their marketing decisions since the metric is not easy to measure when only product performance data are readily available however we argue that ignoring cerelated metrics in the productmarketing domain may mislead managers in allocating marketing  since most studies define ce as a summation of customer lifetime values clv we include the studies on clv in the ce literature  resources since the productbased metrics typically fail to capture the longrun profitability impact on which the ce framework is based for example promotion campaigns that are known to be sales effective and therefore heavily utilized could erode the quality of the customer relationship over time in such a way that longterm profitability is declining jedidi mela and gupta  to make the distinction between relationship and product marketing clearer we categorize various business situations in terms of  the type of relationship between the customer and the firm and  the type of marketing efforts mainly used by the firm see figure  contractual relationship means there exists a finiteperiod eg one year contract between the customer and the firm for the usage of products or services the interpurchase time is predetermined based on the contract and thus the firm can explicitly observe customer retention or defection however if the relationship is noncontractual it is harder to measure the customer’s retentiondefection processes since virtually all customers have different interpurchase times and in general they do not announce their future purchase plans to the firm schmittlein morrison and colombo  schmittlein and peterson  the type of marketing efforts also varies advances in information technology have enabled managers to implement more individualized marketing programs such as catalogues emails and customized coupons inasfar as these marketing activities are aimed at addressable customers blattberg and deighton  it is relatively easy to examine their impact on cerelated metrics such as acquisition and retention rate in  note that one firm or industry could be categorized in multiple cells in figure  for instance a car company can use either email or mass advertising and can have either contractual lease or noncontractual purchase relationships with its customers  contrast when massmarketing efforts eg broadcast advertising are used their ce impact has to be inferred by statistical models this paper expands the scope of the ce paradigm from the relationshipmarketing rm domain ie upper lefthand quadrant in figure  to the productmarketing pm domain ie lower righthand quadrant in figure  insert figure  about here researchers in marketing have suggested several quantitative models to examine ce these studies include  measuring ce given a few critical elements eg berger and nasr   allocating marketing resources under the ce maximization eg blattberg and deighton  and  linking ce to other business metrics eg gupta and lehmann  however the literature has been surprisingly silent in investigating the impact of marketing efforts on ce which should be comprehensively examined before applying the ce paradigm to marketing decision making processes therefore it is necessary to build a model that can  infer the dynamics of ce when some or all critical variables are latent and  capture the impact of marketing efforts on ce these are the main objectives of the current study to achieve these tasks we first discuss the existing literature in ceclv research area and show why the current study is necessary to both managers especially in the pm domain and researchers we then develop an appropriate model to examine the dynamic relationship between marketing efforts and ce next we apply our model to the automobile industry as an empirical illustration based on the empirical result we then discuss managerial implications by simulating ce dynamics for two selected brands  conclusions limitations and a further research agenda will be discussed in the last section literature customer equity is generally defined as “the sum of the discounted lifetime values of all customers” eg blattberg getz and thomas  rust zeithaml and lemon  each element of the definition can be interpreted or measured in a somewhat different way berger and nasr  for instance “all” customers could include the firm’s current customers as well as expected future customers if the ce definition only includes current customers future acquisitions and interactions within the customer group are ignored ie ce is defined in a static way we will refer to this definition as static customer equity sce a frequently used sce metric is due to blattberg and deighton  they suggested a simple formula for sce under fixed acquisition rate a retention rate r acquisition cost a retention cost r contribution margin m and time discount rate δ rrsce am a a m rδ− − r−  this definition is particularly useful in segmenting and thus prioritizing customers in terms of their lifetime values eg hansotia and wang  by ignoring future acquisitions static ce may underestimate the value of customers therefore some researchers include not only the value of current customers but also that of expected future customers in their ce calculation eg gupta lehmann and stuart   in this approach which we call dynamic customer equity dce customers are regarded as renewable resources drezé and bonfrer  in what follows we will use the dynamic definition of customer equity thus equation  needs to be extended to allow for future customer acquisitions as well as interactions between acquisition and retention acquisition rate and retention rate among the elements of customer equity acquisition rate and retention rate are particularly important because they are market response variables and we must understand how they relate to marketing spending however acquisition and retention rates are difficult to obtain in a productmarketing environment since the metrics are constructed by investigating customerbased performance eg number of retained customers instead of productbased performance eg sales volume acquisition and retention rates have been modeled in different ways in the ce literature they have been assumed to be fixed eg berger and nasr  or time varying eg gupta lehmann and stuart  metrics some researchers treat them as exogenous from marketing actions eg wang and splegel  while others consider them as endogenous variables affected by the firm’s marketing effort eg blattberg and deighton  we propose to model acquisition and retention rates as timevarying endogenous variables since our goal is to investigate the dynamic relationship between the firm’s marketing actions and ce via acquisition and retention rates therefore acquisition and retention rates are alternative metrics that capture the firm’s market  hereafter we will use customer equity ce and dynamic customer equity dce interchangeably  performance in addition we will develop a method for measuring acquisition and retention rates in productmarketing scenarios in which managers typically observe only productbased transactions the impact of marketing mix on customer equity blattberg and deighton  measured the impact of marketing on ce by decision calculus assuming onetoone relationships between acquisitionretention spending and acquisitionretention rates respectively however their approach is subject to two important limitations first it does not recognize the dynamic effects of current spending on future acquisition and retention the economics and marketing literature eg heckman  seetharaman and chintagunta  show that customer purchase behavior is not zero order similarly marketing spending levels may depend on past decisions and market responsiveness dekimpe and hanssens  second their approach excludes factors other than marketing spending for example if increased customer satisfaction leads to higher retention acquisition rates may increase as well due to enhanced wordofmouth from satisfied customers thus ce develops over time not only through marketing investments but also by wordofmouth ignoring these forces will likely result in an underestimation of the impact of marketing on ce rust lemon and zeithaml   also investigated the impact of the firm’s marketing efforts on ce through three drivers value equity brand equity and relationship equity individuallevel markov switching matrices were estimated based on each customer’s utility function determined by these three drivers and the firm’s ce was calculated by summing up customer lifetime values inferred from the switching matrix  they calculated how various subdrivers eg advertising could affect ce via the three main drivers using customer survey data however their approach is based on stated responses or intention which may not correctly represent the customer’s actual behavior morrison  model development we propose to link productbased metrics such as sales volume and customerbased metrics such as retentionacquisition rate by a sales decomposition and thereby to enable managers in the pm domain to examine the dynamics of cerelated metrics once we acquire time series of these metrics the dynamic relationship between the marketing mix and ce will be investigated by an econometric timeseries model modeling acquisition rate and retention rate acquisition rate can be defined as “number of acquired prospects or equivalently new customers divided by number of prospects” and retention rate can be defined as “number of retained customers divided by number of existing customers” the difficulty in measuring acquisition rate and retention rate in the pm domain arises from two facts first since purchase frequencies differ across customers managers cannot use calendar time as a time unit for calculating these rates for instance if all customers purchase a firm’s products once a year then the retention rate can be easily calculated by observing their renewal rates however in most product categories customers and prospects have different interpurchase times second the denominators the number of prospects and customers are not easy to observe in many cases as productoriented companies  typically do not have accurate information about their total number of existing customers or prospects we propose using conditional acquisition and retention rates to make them tractable in the pm domain the acquisition rate for a focal brand at time t can be decomposed as nnnsales purchase purchasequantity incidence ap ap pro ap ap prottt ttttp pro p pro pro ptt ttt tap pro protttpro ap ptttnnn sqnann n sq nsqnsqn−−− ⋅  ⋅⋅⋅−  where n is the number of prospects s is sales and q is purchase quantity the superscript p stands for total prospects ap for acquired prospects and pro for prospects who purchase the product category at a particular point of time therefore given purchase quantity and purchase incidence ratio we can write the conditional acquisition rate acq at time t as aptttprotsaacqs∝  by the same logic the conditional retention rate ret at time t can be defined as rctttcustsrrets∝  where the superscript rc stands for retained customers and cus stands for customers who purchase the product category at a particular point of time  the conditional acquisition and retention rates can be measured by examining a simple markov switching matrix as shown in figure  see rust lemon and zeithaml  for a similar approach each brand sales   can be decomposed in two parts sales originating from retained customers   and from acquired prospects   likewise competitors’ total sales   are generated from two sources sales originating from the focal brand’s lost customers  s and from lost prospects   with these decomposed sales we can calculate the conditional acquisition rate and retention rate since osrcsapscslc lps  pro ap lpttcus rc lcttsssssstt in sum given purchase quantity and purchase incidence ratio the acquisition rate and retention rate can be inferred by investigating sales originating from prospects and existing customers therefore equations  and  are the central connections between customer equity and product marketing the longrun impact of marketing efforts on acquisition and retention we investigate the marketing mix effects on acquisition and retention rates by a vector autoregressive var model dekimpe and hanssens  for several reasons first the model can capture the longrun aspects of the relationship among these variables since the measurement of ce should consider future acquisitionretention processes the model should be able to separate shortterm and longterm effects moreover the var model is capable of dealing with evolving variables that do not have fixed means trends and variances second the var model can also capture possible  indirect effects among the variables for example acquisition rates may be affected not only by advertising but also by retention rates inasfar as existing customers generate word of mouth to future prospects impulse response function irf analysis quantifies such complex dynamic interactions among the variables in the var model third due to parsimonious estimation and intuitive metrics eg irf elasticity the var model is easily understood and adapted by managers little  ce model vs sales model the starting point for our ce model is the var sales response model proposed by dekimpe and hanssens         ssllltttkmllltllllcm cmtttucssmc m ucm cmcuψψψψψψψψψ−−−               ∑lmtltllltllm where s is sales volume units or revenue m is a company’s own marketing efforts and cm is competitive marketing efforts this model is easily extendable to multiple marketing mix variables and multiple competitors and operates in the productmarketing domain we transform this model to the relationshipmarketing domain by substituting the sales variable by acquisition rate and retention rate              acqacq lll l tttretret lll lpttlll lmmltttlll lcm cmtttcacq acqret retcmccm cmcεφφφφεφφφφφφφφ εφφφφ ε−−−−                      ∑  for example the impact of own marketing efforts m on the acquisition rate acq  and thereby ce – is investigated by the impulse response of acquisition rate to a shock in own marketing effort we will compare the impact of the marketing mix on acquisition and retention ie the ce domain in model  with its impact on sales from model  in this way we can investigate to what extent the use of productfocus metrics agrees with or conflicts with the purpose of growing customer equity in the next section we apply the proposed model to an empirical dataset and illustrate how the marketing mix effects on ce may be measured via acquisition and retention rates empirical illustration the proposed model is applied to the automobile industry for several reasons first switching behavior is relatively easily observed in this industry since most customers trade in their used cars when purchasing a new vehicle thus researchers can observe the origin of each sales ie from customers vs from prospects based on this tradedin model information second unlike impulsebuying product categories an automobile purchase requires a high involvement of the customer so that the longrun dynamics of acquisition and retention become managerially more meaningful third since automobile manufacturers have both horizontal eg sedan vs suv and vertical eg compact vs luxury product assortments the ce framework is more relevant than in the case of the singleproduct firm which has limited opportunity for crossselling and upselling  data weekly transaction data from  to   weeks in the luxury passenger car product category including suvs are provided by the power information network pin the data are aggregated in terms of tradedin and currentlypurchased brands following pin’s definition of the luxury category results in twelve brands however we will discard three brands  jaguar land rover and saab  due to an insufficient number of transactions the remaining nine brands however cover  of the luxury category the focal market consists of  regional submarkets eg southern california representing over  percent of the us national market on the marketing side the dataset includes pricerelated variables such as vehicle price consumer rebates and annual percentage rate apr for financing these data are supplemented with monthly advertising expenditure data by brand provided by competitive media reporting cmr the expenditures include virtually all media types including magazines newspapers tv radio and outdoor advertisements implemented by both manufacturers and dealers we first calculate daily advertising expenditures for each manufacturer and then convert daily figures into a weekly data series finally product quality and customer satisfaction data are obtained from three annual studies conducted by jd power and associates the automotive performance execution and layout apeal study the initial quality study iqs and the vehicle dependability index vdi study we do not incorporate distribution data in this application because in  by brands we mean makelevel names such as lincoln or lexus the firmlevel names such as ford or toyota will be called manufacturers and product names within brands such as the lincoln ls or the lexus rx will be called models  we implicitly assume that for example advertising for both ford and lincoln will affect purchases of the lincoln brand  the mature us automobile market there were no meaningful changes in dealer networks for the luxury brands during the period under study some descriptive statistics of the variables in the study are presented in table  insert table  about here the timeseries data on acquisition and retention are constructed as follows we first decompose the number of transactions for each brand into two origins purchases by customers who traded in  the same brand and  a different manufacturer’s brand for instance lexus transactions can be separated into purchases originating from lexus or toyota owners and from others such as nissan or ford owners we then decompose total competitors’ sales for each brand into two similar origins for example total competitors’ sales of lexus are divided into sales originating from lexus or toyota customers and from others in sum we construct four sales figures for each brand labeled as  sales originating from retained customers  sales originating from acquired prospects  sales originating from lost customers and  sales originating from lost prospects figure  shows an example of this sales decomposition insert figure  about here  this manufacturerbased data construction enables us to derive ce implications at the firm level including retention and upselling as an illustration lincolntolincoln repeat purchases as well as fordtolincoln upsell purchases are beneficial to ford as a manufacturer  var model specification var model specification requires a test on the stationarity of each endogenous variable we use both the augmented dickey fuller adf test with a null of nonstationarity and the kwiatkowskiphilipsschmidtshin kpss test with a null of stationarity to verify the presence of unit roots in the data when both tests confirm the existence of a unit root we treat the variable as evolving the motivation for this conservative approach is that the conventional adf test can fail to reject the null of nonstationarity too often and therefore overestimates the existence of a unit root kwiatkowski et al  when more than one variable in a var system is found to be evolving we implement johanson’s cointegration test to capture a possible longrun equilibrium among the evolving variables based on the results of unitroot and cointegration tests var systems are specified with corresponding adjustments on the endogenous variables if a variable is found to be nonstationary firstdifferenced forms are used to prevent spurious regressions granger and newbold  if evolving variables are cointegrated errorcorrection terms are added to the var model to measure the system’s adjustment toward the longrun equilibrium dekimpe and hanssens  when all variables are nonstationary with cointegration the ce response model 