g the acura mdx launched during the observation period are included in the var system   apr is used as a proxy for the prime rate  fourth an index variable for product quality and customer satisfaction cs is included by taking the average of annual zscores from the apeal iqs and vdi studies impulse response functions the dynamic impact of one variable on another in the var system is analyzed by irfs we follow the generalized irf approach proposed by pesaran and shin  and introduced in marketing by dekimpe and hanssens  the statistical significance of the irfs is verified by standard errors obtained by a monte carlo simulation eg nijs et al  with  replications in order to make the results comparable we calculate irf elasticities as explained in appendix  all elasticity measures are based on the level form of the original variables for example the response elasticity of retention rate to an advertising shock means a percent change in retention rate to a percent change in advertising expenditure unlike nijs et al  we use arcelasticity instead of pointelasticity since both logit and logarithmic transformations are used in our var systems results unitroot test results as shown in table  the stationarity of each endogenous variable in the var system is verified by the adf test and confirmed by the kpss test eleven of sixty three variables  are found to be nonstationary showing some interesting patterns first the dynamics of product sales do not necessarily coincide with those of customer  the average zscore is used to avoid collinearity since these three scores have intercorrelations between  and   equity metrics for instance while audi’s sales volume is found to evolve the brand’s acquisition and retention rates revert to their longterm means ie stationary this result implies that audi’s observed sales increase does not translate to an increase in its longrun customer equity second retention rates are found to be stationary for all brands while some brands’ acquisition rates are evolutionary in other words in this particular category some brands manage to improve or worsen their efficiency of customer acquisition but none of the brands can change the efficiency of their retention efforts in the long run insert table  about here lastly we find only one case of cointegration among cadillac’s acquisition rate discounting and advertising both trace and maxeigenvalue tests reveal at most one cointegration relationship among the three variables the impact of discounting on customer equity we report the irf elasticities of sales acquisition rate and retention rate to the shock of the discounting index variable in  following the literature in timeseries analysis in marketing eg pauwels hanssens and siddarth  we show irfs with tstatistics greater than unity the table distinguishes between shortterm effects in the same week intermediate effects during the dustsettling weeks and longterm effects after  weeks following the definitions of dekimpe and hanssens  table   the coefficient of the trend variable in the unitroot test equation for audi is significant and positive  insert table  about here as expected from the extant literature eg tellis  discounting ie price promotion has a significant shortterm impact on sales volume in addition seven of nine brands have significant lagged effects and audi and mercedesbenz have longterm effects all brands’ discounting efforts either increase or maintain their sales volume however this positive sales response is not necessarily converted to an improvement in customer equity for instance even though audi has positive intermediate and longterm impacts of discounting on sales volume the responses of retention and acquisition rates are not significant similarly while lincoln has positive shortterm and intermediate effects the brand’s discounting activities only deteriorate its ce in the long run due to a negative longterm impact on acquisition rate the role of discounting efforts in the ce domain differs across brands some brands’ discounting is relatively effective in increasing acquisition rates while other brands are more retention effective for instance extra discounting by lexus increases only its acquisition rate whereas cadillac’s discounting increases only its retention rate while the brand’s acquisition rate is negatively affected by the marketing activity thus we may categorize auto brands in two groups acquisitioneffective and retentioneffective brands the former include all japanese brands acura infiniti and lexus and the latter include american brands cadillac and lincoln managers can use this  detailed unitroot and cointegration test results are available from the first author upon request  the number of lags varies across brands mean   range   to  weeks  information to diagnose the impact of their marketing efforts in more detail and to better allocate marketing resources to existing customers vs prospects we conjecture that these important differences in discounting effectiveness across brands are related to their levels of product quality and customer satisfaction figure  illustrates with simple regression analysis how that the difference between acquisitioneffectiveness and retentioneffectiveness is associated with both initial quality measured by iqs r   and reliability measured by vdi r   we observe that price discounting actions by brands that have relatively higher quality and customer satisfaction are more effective in acquiring new customers than in retaining existing customers and vice versa for brands that have relatively lower quality and customer satisfaction thus if customers are satisfied with a highquality product their repeat purchase decisions are less likely to be affected by their favorite brand’s marketing interventions such as price discounting instead such brands can use discounting more effectively to attract new customers so that the firm can successfully grow its market share in this mature product category this conclusion is corroborated by the observation that three japanese highsatisfaction brands increased their combined annual market share from  to  while two lowersatisfaction us brands decreased theirs from  to  during the threeyear observation period insert figure  about here on average across these nine brands we find that discounting rarely increases a brand’s customer equity in the long run only acura enjoys a longrun positive impact  of discounting on its acquisition rate and no brands can increase longrun retention rates by discounting moreover lincoln and cadillac’s discounting have negative longrun impacts on acquisition rate thus if a manager at lincoln or cadillac only examines the impact of discounting on sales volumes its negative influence on customer equity may go unnoticed in fact cadillac’s shortterm sales increase induced by discounting comes mainly from customer retention but in the long run this discounting has a negative effect on the efficiency of acquiring prospects this finding may also be interpreted as a negative longterm impact of price promotions on the health of brands blattberg briesch and fox  it is also consistent with a result from pauwels et al’s study  that rebates generally do not increase the firm’s shareholder value in the longrun the impact of advertising on customer equity table  shows the impact of advertising on sales volume and ce consistent with past literature eg sethuraman and tellis  advertising has much smaller effects on sales than discounting seven of nine brands do not show significant contemporaneous effects of advertising on sales and only acura and mercedesbenz increase their longterm sales by advertising however as in the case of discounting the impact of advertising on sales volume is not directly translated into the ce domain first positive impacts of advertising on sales do not always correspond to an increase in ce for instance even though bmw enjoys a positive shortterm sales effect of advertising the brand does not significantly increase its customer equity by this advertising similarly audi’s advertising does not significantly impact its sales and actually deteriorates this brand’s customer equity  the observed differences in sales vs ce effects of advertising may be explained as follows acquisition and retention rates are metrics that capture not only a “revealed” topline performance ie acquired prospects and retained customers but also “hidden” lost opportunities ie lost prospects and lost customers given the same level of sales volume acquisition and retention rates could increase or decrease depending on the underlying lost opportunities that are affected by other forces such as competitors’ marketing efforts and wordofmouth between existing customers and prospects for example if extra advertising induces strong competitive reactions over time a brand may face a decrease in customer equity due to tougher competition even though it maintains the same sales volume second consistent with deighton henderson and neslin’s findings  in fpcg categories advertising does not have any direct significant impact on retention rate in the shortrun in deighton et al’s terminology “usage dominance” plays a more important role in this market than “framing” effects between advertising and customer several years of experience with a luxury automobile makes the evidence of the product quality “unambiguous” hoch and ha  so that advertising can hardly affect customer’s judgment of the product while we find some significant intermediate effects of advertising on retention rate these impacts may be explained by competitive reactions performance feedback and wordofmouth effects decomposing these dynamic effects pauwels  is an interesting topic for future research third the shortterm and intermediate impact of advertising on acquisition rate supports the proposition that advertising provides valuable information to customers and thus increases competition among brands only mercedesbenz has a positive longterm  effect of advertising on acquisition rate but audi infiniti and volvo have only negative impacts other brands do not have any significant impacts interestingly among nine brands infiniti  market share and audi  market share are the smallest brands in terms of market share and infiniti volvo and audi are second third and fourth cheapest brands respectively in terms of average vehicle prices mercedesbenz  market share which has a positive longterm impact of advertising has the biggest market share and is the most expensive brand in the product category this result can be interpreted that for smaller brands direct persuasive effects are dominated by cross effects of competitive reactions by other brands bigger brands have advantages in advertising in the longrun kent and allen  nonsignificant advertising effects on acquisition for five of nine brands show that there exists little switching from competitive brands to the advertising brands raj  in fact in a recent study by banerjee and bandyopadhyay  the authors analytically showed that given a significant portion of customers who have latent inertia of repeat purchase advertising is not an effective competitive marketing tool for small firms who generally compete on the basis of price insert table  about here so far we have examined the dynamic impact of marketing on acquisition and retention rates using these results one can investigate how the firm’s marketing mix affects its dce which is a nontrivial combination of acquisition rate retention rate marketing costs contribution margins and time discount factors in the next section we numerically illustrate the impact of an extra marketing intervention on dce and other  managerially relevant metrics such as number of customers and profits we describe how dynamic customer equity unfolds over time for two different brands who initiate a discounting effort that has different dynamic effects on their acquisition and retention rates a numerical simulation of customer equity we first derive dce at time t as a function of conditional retention rate r conditional acquisition rate a and the current number of existing customers nt total number of customers in the product category nc retention cost per customer r acquisition cost per prospect a  category sales sc and time discount factor δ assumptions and derivations can be found in appendix  as a result ce evaluated at time t can be expressed as    titiicctccvdcenarrmam samansasnraδδδ∞− − −−∑c  where vt stands for the value of customers at time t note that this derivation is an extension of blattberg and deighton’s  sce formula it incorporates the dynamic aspects of customer equity as well as a modified analytical solution to gupta et al’s  discrete version of customer equity calculation we simulate how an unexpected marketing intervention such as a  extra discount affect the future stream of number of customers profits and customer equity for  two brands acura and lincoln we use each brand’s impulse response of acquisition rate retention rate and discounting to a discounting shock in order to calculate the total impact of this  extra discount note that acura enjoys a longterm positive impact of discounting on acquisition rate while lincoln has a negative impact moreover lincoln’s extra discount has a longer decision inertia  weeks than acura’s  weeks resulting in more supplemental spending in the future insert table  about here as shown in table  we first calculate the focal metrics under normal business conditions derived from the data and several assumptions explained in appendix  for instance using sample averages of vehicle price retention rate and acquisition rate we are able to calculate the status quo scenario under the assumptions on current number of customers total product category sales contribution margin and time discount factor using the same assumptions we then recalculate number of customers profit per period and customer equity with a  extra discount by using the irf elasticity estimated from the model by comparing these two scenarios ie status quo vs marketing intervention we investigate how the firm’s marketing mix affects cerelated metrics in this numerical illustration acura successfully develops its ce even in the status quo scenario mainly due to its high average retention rate  and acquisition rate  the brand also expands its customer pool and achieves higher perperiod profits over time implementing the extra marketing activity helps acura increase its ce  for ease of exposition we use the notation r and a for conditional retention and acquisition rate  beyond the status quo scenario a main driver of this increase is the longterm effect of discounting on acquisition rate an interesting difference exists between shortterm profit and customer equity in the same week when the extra discount is implemented acura’s profit is significantly reduced  of status quo profit but its customer equity increases  of status quo ce due to the expected customer value the marketing effort will generate in the future on the other hand lincoln fails to increase its ce by discounting efforts one year after the marketing intervention the brand only achieves  of its statusquo customer equity note that lincoln’s decrease in number of customers is small  decrease in one year compared to its reduction in ce the main reasons for the ce decline for lincoln are the inertia in the company’s decision process and the inefficiency of acquiring new customers that is while acura’s incremental marketing efforts quickly dissipate back to normal lincoln keeps spending at higher levels without achieving higher market response ie acquisition and retention rates moreover in the long run the brand’s acquisition rate is negatively affected by the extra marketing effort as a result the extra marketing intervention by lincoln while sales effective in the short run has a negative impact on the brand’s future ce development conclusion in this paper we show how product marketers can infer the impact of their marketing mix efforts on the dynamics of customer equity via retention rate and acquisition rate using a series of switching matrices we calculate four different sales respectively  figures for each brand viz sales originating from existing customers new customers lost customers and lost prospects we then construct the time series of two core elements of ce retention rate and acquisition rate the longrun impact of marketing mix efforts on ce is investigated by estimating var models and calculating impulse responses of retention rate and acquisition rate to the shock of corresponding marketing efforts the main contribution of this paper is to derive customerequity metrics from conventional productbased metrics such as sales and thus to derive the longterm customerrelationship consequences of various productmarketing actions the proposed model enables managers to assess the health of their brands by comparing the impact of marketing efforts on customer equity vs sales by comparing these impacts managers can reallocate their marketing resources to maximize the longterm value of the firm as an example in our empirical illustration even though lincoln’s discounting has a positive shortterm and intermediate impact on sales volume it has a negative longrun impact on customer equity and thus should be avoided as much as possible the main findings of this paper can be summarized as follows • in the product marketing environment acquisition rate and retention rate can be measured by decomposing sales into four parts sales from existing customers from new customers from lost customers and from lost prospects • the impact of the marketing mix on customer equity is different from its impact on sales in an empirical illustration for the automobile industry both discounting and advertising increase product sales but discounting does not increase customer equity in the longrun only one of nine brands increases its longterm acquisition rate by advertising  • brands differ in the source of their ce increase induced by discounting efforts higherquality brands are more acquisitioneffective and lowerquality brands are more retentioneffective • advertising does not have a significant impact on retention rate both contemporaneously and in the longrun • the impact of advertising on acquisition rate is different across brands advertising by smallshare and cheaper brands has a negative impact on their acquisition rate whereas advertising by largeshare and expensive brands increases their acquisition rates this paper has several limitations that offer opportunity for further research first there exist other endogenous drivers of customer equity assumed to be exogenous in this paper for example examining how marketing activities affect the future contribution margin for different customer cohorts is an interesting issue reinartz and kumar   second customer equity may be more sensitive to individualized marketing efforts such as direct mail than mass marketing efforts such as discounting and advertising if the firm uses different marketing strategies with existing customers vs prospects a model may be developed that captures retention and acquisition effectiveness separately for each third different product categories need to be studied while our model can be extended to fastmoving consumer products the sales decomposition for such categories is a challenging task because the ownershipbased grouping of existing vs new customers in this paper may no longer be appropriate  table  descriptive statistics of data acura audi mercedes benz bmw cadillac infiniti lexus lincoln volvonumber of transactionsmean          sd          min          max          vehicle price mean          sd          min          max          rebate mean          sd          min          max          apr mean          sd          min          max          advertising expenditure kmean          sd          min          max          number of obse